      "role": "user",
      "content": "get what u mean with the gloves thing. but what's the \"spooky\" part exactly? like why did einstein call it that if it's just about particles being connected? it sounds like there's something more going on than just math.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein called it \"spooky\" because he believed the universe should be \"local,\" meaning information can't travel faster than light, and objects only have definite properties when you look at them. He thought the \"glove\" analogy was perfect because the gloves *already* decided which way they were facing the moment they were packed, just like he thought the particles had hidden \"instructions\" (hidden variables) written inside them.\n\nThe \"spooky\" part is that experiments proved Einstein wrong about the gloves. In quantum entanglement, the particles *don't* have a decided state until you measure them. It's not that a signal zips across the distance to tell the second particle what to do; it's that the two particles share a single, unified existence. Measuring one doesn't just reveal a pre-existing fact; it actively *creates* the reality for the other instantly.\n\nThink of it like this: If you have two entangled particles, they aren't two separate things floating in space. They are more like a single, stretched-out entity that spans the distance between them. When you poke one end, the whole thing reacts immediately, even if the other end is light-years away. It's like a single",
      "source": "target",
