    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to feel that way; that \"missing link\" is exactly what Einstein was hunting for, and it's the most frustrating part for anyone trying to wrap their head around it. It feels less like a neat mathematical equation and more like a cosmic glitch where the rules of logic get bent.\n\nBut here is the thing about the universe: it doesn't actually use a \"force\" or a \"signal\" to coordinate this. If there were a signal traveling between the particles, it would take time to get there, and we would see a delay. Since there is no delay, the universe isn't sending a message; it's simply refusing to let the two particles be separate entities in the first place.\n\nThink of it like this: Imagine you have two identical, blank pieces of paper floating in a room. In the classical world, you could write \"Heads\" on one and \"Tails\" on the other beforehand. But in the quantum world, the papers are blank until someone looks at them. The moment you look at Paper A and see \"Heads,\" Paper B *instantly* becomes \"Tails\" not because a messenger ran from A to B, but because the two papers were never two separate",
